Misplaced military focus

In 2003, 1 .2 billion people lived on less
than $1 per day. Half or more of the popu-
lation in the 49 least—developed countries
are estimated to live at that
absolute poverty line. Another
2.8 billion lived on less than
$2.

That United Nations list
of 49 poorest nations in the
world runs like a who’s who
of the most unstable countries
in the world: Afghanistan,
Burundi, Central African
Republic, Democratic
Republic of Congo, Haiti,
Liberia, Rwanda, Sierra
Leone, Somalia, Sudan — on
and on it goes. Not surprising-
ly, and virtually without exception, these
countries have also witnessed tremendous
violations of human rights and the targeting
of civilians in military action.

In Israel and Palestine, the most visible
of the ﬁghts against terror continues. Over
3 million Palestinians are refugees without
a state. The West Bank is divided into
roughly 300 enclaves by Israeli check-
points, settlements and roadblocks.
Seventy—ﬁve percent of Palestinians live on
less than $2 a day and unemployment runs
well over 50 percent. '

The tie between poverty and violence
is not a coincidence.

What is interest, however, is that a
study of the 21 richest countries and their
commitment to the development of poor
countries ranked the United States 20th out
of those nations, ahead of only Japan. The
study, created by the Center for Global
Development and Foreign Policy maga-
zine, gauged policies concerning aid, trade,
investment, migration, peacekeeping and
enviromnent according to help or harm
done to poor nations. On a 10-point scale,
the United States scored above a 3.0 only
once, and our average was a jaw—dropping
2.6.

The delusion that we as a country con-
tribute a lot of money to foreign aid could
not be further from the truth. While we
account for a whopping 22 percent of the
entire world’s economy, only one-tenth of 1
percent of our gross domestic product‘ is
distributed in foreign aid. Meanwhile, we

  

