spend over 25 percent of our discretionary
budget on defense spending at a time when
the major security threat — terrorism — does
not require the colossal mili-
tary we employ, but rather
accurate intelligence and spe-
cialized forces. That quarter of
the budget equates to over 400
billion dollars; that is the most
in the world. It totals more
than the next nine countries -
China, Russia, France, United
Kingdom, Germany, Italy,
India, Japan and Saudi Arabia
— combined. Also, it is more
than four times what we com-
mit to education and health
care together.

Presidential candidates George W.
Bush and John Kerry are both in a heated
race to present themselves as more quali-
ﬁed in ﬁghting the war on terror.
Unforttmately, the debate is focused on mil-
itary credentials and voting on military
issues. And it is the wrong focus. This is not
an issue of Republicans or Democrats. It is
one of a collective American misconcep-
tion that the solution to terrorism is solely a
military one.

No military, no matter how strong, can
prevent acts of terrorism on civilians —
September 11, 2001, proved that. Terrorism
is a tactic and cannot be eliminated alto-
gether, but it can be dealt with through
efforts towards eliminating its roots.
Poverty plays an essential role in this com-
plex equation.

Unforttmately, our historical self-inter-
est manifests itself in our lack of concern
for plight, starvation and death, unless it is

 

. of consequence domestically. A sense of

moral responsibility to help those less for-
trmate — affordably, when comparing the
values of dollars to human life — nonethe-
less remains absent ﬁom our society. Still,
this is not a matter of initiating action by
way of guilt or idealistic humanitarianism.
Instead, our lack of commitment toward
improving the living standards of those
most desperate remains a fundamental hur-
dle to defeating terrorism in the long run.

